Sal Salerno (from Modesto) and I went to Klamath Glen to try and refind the Chestnut-sided Warbler that was found by Lucas Brug yesterday. The bird was very easy to find; it was in the far corner on the river side of the boat ramp parking lot at the end of Terwer Riffle Road. The bird gave us very good looks. Alex Lamb also joined us shortly after we arrived. All observations were from the parking lot area and the western edge of MacBeth Airfield, where the Grasshopper Sparrow was present and singing. I came out to the jetty to do a seawatch for an hour but didn''t even make it out to the tip of jetty due to the huge numbers of birds present on the east side of the jetty, busy in a huge feeding frenzy on small baitfish spawning at the time. I estimated about 5,000 gulls along being present with 60% Heermann''s, 30% Westerns, and 10% California Gulls. The Glaucous Gull may be the same one that was seen by another observer that same day or the day before. The number of Common Murre''s present was nothing short of phenomenal and were so thick on the water that I saw 2 fisherman accidentally hook 2 separate birds, of course releasing them. Also 2 large salmon were caught here while birding. Amazing.

Birding with Tom and Thomas Nolan, mostly scanning from tip of North Jetty.--Distant view of Black-footed Albatross: large, distinctive flight, all dark.  There were at least 3-4 shearwaters in vicinity of the albatross that were dwarfed by the albatross (alby was 2-3x larger at least).  Couldn''t be sure shearwaters were sooty because couldn''t get a read on underwing; suspect they were SOSH.--Excellent photos of Surfbirds and Tattlers.--100s of murres in bay and cruising past tip of jetty.--

I walked from the trail that begins at the northwestern corner of the boat ramp parking lot at the park, doing some light trail maintenance along the way. I walked out to the gravel bar and proceeded to walk along the waters edge almost all the way to the mouth of the Mad River. I then walked back the way I came due to me forgetting my walking/trail clearing stick. --The Sooty Shearwaters and scoters were all seen while briefly scoping the ocean on the ocean side of the Mad River Spit.--The Redstart was an adult male and quickly came in--along with a McGillivray''s  and 2 Wilson''s Warblers--to my pishing. It was in the willow patch that is accessed from the trail from the beach parking lot. High tide at Arcata Wharf was around 1258, making for nice shorebirding conditions and lot''s of activity.

Coverage for Santa Clarita CBC.  Mostly cloudy, becoming about 60% clear by late morning.  Calm, to light northwesterly breeze. 42-60 deg F. Lagoon level fairly low, with much rock exposed at dam/outflow area. I covered the entire Castaic Lagoon area, first working the west side and then moving over to the east side.  I also checked the riparian drainage and pine grove at the north end.  Red-necked Grebe (juvenile) and White-winged Scoter (female) both photodocumented, as was the first-cycle Mew Gull.

TRIP COMMENTS: Most birds were too distant to get any kind of accurate counts in the failing light. The Short-eared Owl had been seen recently in the same area. Birding with Frances Oliver, Leigh Johnson, and Alex Thomas.

I had a frustrating morning here as very early I got on three black and white alcids on the water fairly distant. As it finally was getting light enough to see details at high end of my zoom (60X), a fisherman blocked my view and I wasn’t able to relocate the birds. Lots of fisherman were present today (lot of hook-ups today unlike previous days), but also a lot more bird activity, at least terns, right off the end of the pier. Although the murrelets flapped their wings several times, it was usually at the wrong angle. A few times it appeared grayish, which under the lighting conditions today (low clouds and early – before 6 am), meant the underwing linings were probably white and they were probably Xantus’s Murrelets.

TRIP COMMENTS: Conducting the Orange County Northeastern Christmas Bird Count, in Nancy Kenyon and Neal Anderson's area (Irvine Lake and the nearby Hick's/Blue Diamond Haul Road, along with portions of the private camps along the haul road). This was the first year (I believe) that I was finally able to get out of my old (area leader) assignments for the NE count (for like 20-25 years doing the O'Neill Regional Park and vicinity, then maybe 6 or 8 years being area leader of the Lemon/Cowan Heights area). COVERAGE: Besides doing the entire south and southeast shorelines of the lake, the west slope (a road that goes up to some old dwellings on the upper west slope), we also drove out the haul roads, out east of the lake, and then followed the road to the southeast, across Santiago Canyon Road, and then into the Lower Limestone Canyon. We birded the lower 1/2 mile of Limestone (just south of Santiago Can. Rd.  WEATHER: Mostly clear (except for a 30-40% cover of high thin clouds). Calm to 5mph breezes. About 35 (deg. F) at start!  Warming to a high 60s high. HABITATS:  Open water of the lake, but little to almost no marsh-type vegetation, except possibly for the northeastern corner, where Santiago Creek feeds into the lake, but we couldn't get over to that area. Also coastal sage scrub; mixed sage scrub/chaparral; some limited chaparral and coast live oak woodland on north-slope terrain at southeast and eastern edges of the lake; fairly small areas of riparian habitat that were connected to small tributaries to the lake on the southwestern and southeastern sides; and exotic plantings (lots of pines, some sycamore, eucalyptus, and Lombardy poplars and cottonwoods, etc., associated with the private camps on the east side). ----The following was taken directly from my birding notes for this date and location. ----Abbreviations:  IL = Irvine Lake;  HR = Haul Road.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Notes say: "Roughly 5 or 6 I felt. Nancy reported 8 on our official tally form for Irvine Lake, but I don't think it was quite thst many. I don't think we ever had more than 3 in sight at once."

The northward dispersal of Elegant Terns has begun; one thousand six hundred--(1600) were present on the Delta Beach mudflats. Other birds of interest--included Common Tern (2 apparent adults, 5 first and second-summer types),--Surfbird (3 molting adults), Long-billed Dowitcher (1 molting adult), and--Wilson's Phalarope (3 molting adults, 2 molting juvs).----Lea Squires had more Elegant Terns (400) on North Island. She also had the--first juvenal plumaged Heermann's Gulls (8) I've heard of this year.----On the way home there even more Elegant Terns (1000+) on the South Bay--Biological Study Area mudflats (and I imagine a few Commons mixed in).

LETE survey at DBS--An adult Black Tern in nearly full alternate plumage was foraging over--central San Diego Bay this morning. It bathed briefly at Delta Beach before--flying west towards the ocean. This bird is not chaseable but the salt ponds--at the south end of the bay are probably worth a look.

TRIP COMMENTS: This represents a walk from the middle parking lot to the north pond.  I was scouting for tomorrow''s trip.  The Tundra Swans took off from the northeast pond, and flew over my head, so they got counted again!  The Snipe were a nice surprise.  The Brant was resting in the pond.  The BBPlover was a very light juvenile, flecked with a bit of gold.  I patiently watched until it raised its tail, then its wings, revealing the diagnostic marks.  In the meantime, a yellowlegs had walked by it, and been dwarfed by it, which helped identify both birds.  Cool, but not as cold as I had been led to believe.

LOCALITY: Ano Nuevo SP--Visitors Center, Elephant Seals and trails
TRIP COMMENTS: Spent most of the day prowling the bluffs at Ano Nuevo with my scope. Puffins, Brant and Oystercatchers were all just south of the park at the SMC/SCZ county line, at a point visible from the park. Both puffins were white-faced individuals. Ancient Murrelet, a life bird, floated by slowly on calm water just a hundred yards offshore giving extended opportunity for study of tiny, stubby pale bill, black chin above otherwise white underparts, clean white extending up across neck to a point behind the eye, dark gray back. Brown Pelican count is conservative; it was quite a show. Pelagic Cormorant count is even more conservative and is probably very low as birds were coming and going a lot. I did confirm 23 active PECO nests on the cliffs however, with sitting birds in place on the nests. There were probably more nests too; I was primarily in search of alcids and did not look as hard as I might have although the numbers given here are solid in terms of minimum numbers of confirmed individuals.

SPECIES COMMENTS: About 2 weeks ago, I saw an Osprey flying very low and slow over a treetop at the Rt. 85 northbound offramp onto Almaden Expwy. The bird was acting like an Osprey that is trying to break sticks off a tree, but it flew on without touching the tree. On 5 March, someone in our office saw an Osprey placing sticks "on a pole" along Rt. 85 nearby. This morning I saw the bird break a stick off the aforementioned tree and carry it to the top of an electrical pole on the northeast side of the 85/Almaden Expwy. interchange (right next to the 85 roadway). There were a few other sticks on the top of the pole already. I this bird has been messing around in the area for two weeks, it's not making much progress toward a completed nest, so it may be an unpaired bird. [Postscript - the bird never made any more progress on the nest]

Several active osprey nests on this stretch of river also.

Observations from a bicycle ride to Clear Creek and back on hiway 96. Fire in the canyon!  Backing fire along a couple of mile stretch, drift smoke and overall smoky conditions.  Hot when starting, high 90''s cooling to high 70''s by dusk. Mature eagle and immature eagle. Watched large black bear for several minutes. Also saw striped skunk and gray fox during the ride. Several hotshot crews were present also.

I continued on to Lower Klamath NWR & Tule Lake. Lots of BLACK TERNS & a few FRANKLIN''S GULL cruised the water at Tule Lake; SNOWY EGRETS & COMMON YELLOWTHROATS were in the marsh area, and lots of ducks & babies everywhere else. White Lake was dry.
